and Welsh contexts, and as such was narrated by a number of chroniclers, including Adam Usk, John Capgrave, Thomas Walsingham and Edward Halle. Theyoffer a range of perspectives on the events, as well as portrayals of the main characters (especially, of course, Glyndwr himself), the communities involved, and Wales. This book studies the representations of the revolt in English chronicles, from 1400 up to1580. It focuses on the narrative strategies employed, offers a new reading of the texts as literary constructs, and explores the information they present. Alicia Marchant is a ResearchAssociate in the ARC Centre of Excellence for the History of Emotions at the University of Western Australia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDiscourse analysis, Narrative. 0aHistoriographyxHistoryyTo 1500zGreat Britain. 0aHistoriographyzGreat BritainxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aNational characteristics. 0aNationalismzWales. 0aSpace and time. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChroniclers.  aEnglish Chronicles.  aHistory.  aMedieval.  aMiddle Ages.  aOwain Glyndwr.  aRepresentation.  aUprising.  aWales.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782043539?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782043539423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782043539/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles